description.narrative:
The major project results achieved so far are the following:
- elaboration and approval of the Project Engagement Strategy for 2018-2020 with a purpose to support the GoU in establishing coordination platform on peacebuilding and recovery and to deliver select pilots in the areas defined as critical gaps and with a potential to be expanded;
- the design and launch of the Collaborative Leadership for Resilience and Development dialogue series, which brought together diverse representatives from Ukrainian Ministries and local authorities from eastern Ukraine to promote cross-Governmental communication, strategy, and joint action in response to the continued conflict;
- in partnership with Government of Ukraine, UN Office of the Coordinator for Humanitarian Affairs, UN Resident Representative’s Office, and a Ukrainian Mapping Institute, further development and dissemination of a geocoded Data Portal on Peacebuilding and Recovery that brings together humanitarian and development data into one interface to support recovery strategy and coordination;
- design of a GoU-led Coordination Platform on Peacebuilding and Recovery based on national and international consultations including a GoU-convened event that gathered over 50 representatives of national Ministries, regional authorities, non-governmental organizations, and international agencies to solicit lessons regarding coordination efforts to date and the way forward;
- implementation and finalization of a pilot on psychosocial support to conflict-affected populations including field training and counselling delivered in Luhansk and Donetsk oblasts; and lessons learned and coordination events on pilot results to promote future scale-up and expansion of activities;
- Based on recommendations of Ukrainian officials at the CL4RD event, the launch of a new MPTF-financed study on Economic Recovery of the Donbas to create an evidence-based analysis to drive future policies and investments in socio-economic recovery of the region. 2019 was a year of political transition in Ukraine, and the new Government team has placed a priority on policies and programming to promote recovery and reintegration of eastern Ukraine. MPTF team efforts focused on developing the Bank’s relationship and work program in coordination with the newly merged Ministry of Temporarily Occupied Territories and Internally Displaced Persons (MVTOT) as a new Government counterpart for MPTF activities; and on aligning MPTF activities with new administration priorities. Dialogue with broader range of national stakeholders and inter-government structures leading conflict-recovery efforts was also continued;
- The World Bank, at the request of the Presidential Administration at the Mariupol Investment Forum in October 2019, invested in exploring the development of a possible Partnership Fund on Recovery and Reintegration that would build on the current MPTF and focus on the Government’s new recovery and reintegration priorities. Discussions with MPTF donors and other international partners have not resulted in any concrete output, and would have probably lead to further discussions and coordination among the key donors working in the area without involvement of the WB. The first question to answer is what is to be done, and than who can do that the best (WB is one of the options);
- Due to lengthy discussions about the possible strategy to utilize the remaining MPTF balance (at the moment 530 00 USD), the next meeting of the MPTF Executive Board is postponed. The meeting shall review progress of MPTF activities to date and  consider additional proposals for funding with remaining MPTF financing.
- Lack of full staff to work with MPTF in Kyiv has negatively impacted the development and implementation of the project. Canada and Sweden have raised this issue with the WB on several occasions, however the World Bank does plan to expand its office / presence in Ukraine.
